AB  - A review of the agricultural system of the Atlantic Rainforest traditional Caicara populations was undertaken, through a comparative and historical approach of authors discussing slash-and-burn agriculture in Tropical Forests. A comparative numerical analysis of authors who have published data on Caicara gardens (rocas) was carried through, considering several variable involved in the system, including the historical-regional setting. The results obtained were: average size of gardens (0.42 ha), average time of cultivation (3.1 years), average fallow time (7.8 years), human occupation area, population size and cultivated area. The area needed for the continuity of the system was calculated for two different scenarios. The calculations presented were subjected to a degree of approximation and should be taken as indicative, as a sketch of the profile of some variables involved in Caicara gardens, and as a contribution for future research concerning this subject. The results obtained were compared with international data, and one of the hypotheses risen for the abandonment of agriculture in some Caicara populations, in the past, was the decrease in productivity, due to high population densities.
