AB  - The European Union produces about 1 billion of agriculture, forest and food processing wastes or by-products. These materials are partially used as soil amendment, animal feeding, energy source, etc. However, the majority of these wastes or by-product are either abandoned on the production site or simply incinerated because of their bulky volume.
   Controlled biodegradation of mixtures of these wastes or by-products allow rough tailoring of its chemical constituents. The generated organic substrate was tested for eliminating heavy metal ions 'HMI' from synthetic solutions. It was possible to recover more than 95 % of HMI contained in the solution. Elution of the substrate saturated by HMI was possible by using diluted acids and leads to the recuperate the quasi totality of FIMI and the organic substrate was used for several cycles of HMI fixation and elution. The retention capacity of these materials varies as function of the composition of the mixture of wastes, pH, the HMI nature, the initial concentration, etc.
   In some cases, pyrolysis or incineration of the saturated substrate generate residues rich in heavy metal compounds. Such residues have metals' concentration that may exceed the natural ores or concentrates. It can be recycled for secondary metal production. This may avoid the waste disposal of such material in spite of their small volume.
